- I'll talk to him.
- No.

38:13.560 --> 38:14.786
He'll talk to me.
He won't talk to you.

38:14.840 --> 38:18.183
- I said no!
- Interpol's a real thing?

38:18.240 --> 38:21.389
I'm not going to cut
my fuckin' leg off.

38:21.480 --> 38:23.230
- Five minutes.
- Get outta here, Francie.

38:23.320 --> 38:24.910
- Crunch... Yeah, OK.
- Now.

38:30.240 --> 38:33.105
- Crunch.
- Sam?

38:34.920 --> 38:38.422
Men of our vintage
should be retired.

38:40.880 --> 38:42.982
You know, when I heard you were
working for the other side,

38:43.040 --> 38:46.349
I just couldn't believe it.

38:46.400 --> 38:49.265
At least tell me they don't
make you wear a wire.

38:49.320 --> 38:52.264
No. They don't make me wear a wire.

38:52.320 --> 38:56.744
And I get to see some fine art.

38:56.800 --> 39:00.985
So... what do you think they're
talking about down there?

39:02.560 --> 39:04.071
Still about the art, huh?

39:05.040 --> 39:06.983
My mother got me into it.

39:07.040 --> 39:11.862
We were always hard up,
but she did her best.

39:11.920 --> 39:14.421
Worked as a barmaid between kids.

39:16.520 --> 39:18.384
When I was ten or 11,

39:18.440 --> 39:22.306
she took me to the
V and A in London.

39:23.640 --> 39:26.220
And I saw an object
that blew my mind.

39:27.880 --> 39:33.111
It was a drinking cup fashioned
from a single piece of jade.

39:33.160 --> 39:38.061
It was just a cup,
but it was perfect.

39:38.120 --> 39:41.667
And it made me look at
everything differently.

39:41.720 --> 39:46.906
Turner, Monet, Vermeer,
those guys kept my eyes open.

39:46.960 --> 39:52.271
It was a feeling I had,
a completeness when art touched me.

39:54.560 --> 39:59.461
I only started getting into trouble
when I wanted to possess it.

40:01.040 --> 40:05.225
And you... what makes you do it?

40:05.280 --> 40:06.506
Money.

40:06.560 --> 40:09.630
Well, at least you're honest.

40:09.680 --> 40:12.465
It's always nice to know...

40:13.560 --> 40:15.981
who you can trust.

40:16.040 --> 40:18.461
I'm gonna find this painting.

40:18.560 --> 40:22.870
Not because I want to get you
or your brother in trouble.

40:22.920 --> 40:26.024
I just want to hold it.

40:29.800 --> 40:32.426
Let me ask you a question.

40:32.480 --> 40:34.548
You ever seen the
inside of Sing-Sing?

40:34.600 --> 40:37.306
- I haven't.
- 'Cause I know a lot of guys

40:37.360 --> 40:40.191
who would like to fuck
you inside there.

40:42.000 --> 40:44.148
Are you hitting on me?

40:46.440 --> 40:47.951
I will...

40:48.000 --> 40:49.386
Fuck!

40:49.440 --> 40:52.191
It's been a breath of fresh air.

40:52.240 --> 40:54.229
Looking good, Sam.

40:59.680 --> 41:01.782
Interpol? Fucking Interpol?!

41:01.840 --> 41:05.069
I'm not going to fuckin' prison!
I'm not cut out for that shit!

41:05.120 --> 41:06.949
You see these fuckin' arms, man?

41:07.000 --> 41:10.388
These wet noodles will prevent
very few prison rapes.

41:10.440 --> 41:12.542
Francie, I promise you
on my mother's eyes,

41:12.600 --> 41:15.021
- you're gonna be fine.
- You don't know that.

41:15.080 --> 41:19.469
You gotta trust me. Look,
ever since I've been back,

41:19.520 --> 41:23.227
you've been there for
me like nobody else.

41:23.280 --> 41:28.546
Now... I might have to
toss in the "f" word here

41:28.600 --> 41:32.386
to make this a bit easier but...
I fuckin' love you, man.

41:32.440 --> 41:34.747
OK, my turn.

41:36.240 --> 41:37.580
That has to be Guy.

41:40.400 --> 41:42.946
All right, Guy just landed
and we got a little problem.

41:43.000 --> 41:46.309
- Interpol.
- All right. Well, we'll adapt.

41:46.360 --> 41:48.303
OK?

41:51.880 --> 41:53.106
So?

41:54.600 --> 41:57.783
I'm curious to know what
kind of game you're running?

41:57.840 --> 42:00.830
I was curious about your game.

42:00.880 --> 42:04.587
We need to get on the same page.

42:04.640 --> 42:06.868
What do we do first?

42:06.960 --> 42:08.300
First, we're gonna need a fake.

42:08.360 --> 42:11.066
- How good must it look?
- Good enough to fool the eye.

42:12.240 --> 42:15.583
<i>Identical on the outside,
inside doesn't matter.</i>

42:15.640 --> 42:18.220
You've got four days.

42:18.280 --> 42:21.589
Crunch, I'm sorry for making
fun of your Trojan Horse idea

42:21.680 --> 42:22.799
because it actually plays.

42:22.800 --> 42:25.710
We're gonna hide that fake in
a Trojan Horse of our own.

42:25.760 --> 42:27.079
Something that draws attention.

42:27.080 --> 42:29.069
Paddy, see what you
can come up with.

42:29.120 --> 42:31.951
I got the perfect thing in mind.

42:32.000 --> 42:33.750
I don't know, what do you think?

42:33.800 --> 42:36.983
It makes me feel...

42:37.040 --> 42:40.349
safe and scared.

42:41.520 --> 42:43.384
Mostly scared.

42:43.440 --> 42:46.942
It's weird. It's
like it follows you.

42:48.080 --> 42:50.831
First, you caress.

42:50.920 --> 42:54.263
Too rough, she cracks.

42:54.320 --> 42:57.264
Too soft, she will not
succumb to the touch.

42:57.320 --> 43:03.143
Just right. It's you. Ahh.

43:04.800 --> 43:06.868
Then we need to get our
horse into their corral.

43:06.920 --> 43:11.264
But, how? You say this border
station, they inspect everything.

43:11.320 --> 43:14.424
Exactly. Everything going
in, everything going out.

43:14.480 --> 43:17.470
<i>We can't walk in our fake
or walk out our original.</i>

43:17.520 --> 43:20.942
So we're gonna get them
to take it in for us.

43:21.000 --> 43:25.867
We're going to use our sullied
reputation to our advantage for once.

43:28.400 --> 43:30.582
<i>Crunch sets off the
bells and whistles.</i>

43:32.040 --> 43:35.667
<i>There's a standard 30-day
impound on undocumented art.</i>

43:35.720 --> 43:38.585
<i>And, because it's Crunch,
convicted art thief,</i>

43:38.640 --> 43:41.664
<i>transporting art without
the proper paperwork,</i>

43:41.760 --> 43:44.625
<i>they're gonna call the gallery
where it was purchased right away,</i>

43:44.720 --> 43:46.788
<i>to make sure that it's not stolen.</i>

43:46.840 --> 43:49.261
<i>But it ain't goin' anywhere
until Crunch shows up</i>

43:49.320 --> 43:51.900
<i>with the proof of
ownership, which we've got.</i>

43:51.960 --> 43:54.222
<i>And we know where it's being kept.</i>

43:54.280 --> 43:56.303
The toad is in the hole.

43:56.400 --> 43:57.945
<i>What the fuck are
you talking about?</i>

43:58.000 --> 44:01.422
The fuckin' huge vagina is
in the border station now.

44:01.480 --> 44:05.107
<i>Because of Crunch's record,
Interpol will be brought in.</i>

44:05.200 --> 44:08.782
<i>But, since no crime has been
committed, they can't touch us.</i>

44:08.840 --> 44:11.102
What the hell am I looking at?

44:11.160 --> 44:14.389
It's four foot high and
staring you in the face.

44:14.440 --> 44:16.861
And on the day,
what about Interpol?

44:16.960 --> 44:19.427
They're going to be watching
us, which we need to fix.

44:19.480 --> 44:21.309
Francie and I will distract them

44:21.360 --> 44:23.827
while the switch goes down
at the border station.

44:23.880 --> 44:27.701
But most important thing is we've
gotta deal with Olga Something-Long.

44:27.760 --> 44:31.421
- Paddy?
- Well, that'll be something hard.

44:31.520 --> 44:34.544
Things between Olga and me
are rough as a bear's arse.

44:34.600 --> 44:36.039
She's got to miss that appointment.

44:36.040 --> 44:38.541
But, more importantly,
is we need those forms.

44:38.600 --> 44:41.943
- No paperwork, no access.
- I'll start tomorrow.

44:49.600 --> 44:53.625
- Olga, darlin'.
- Oh, no.

44:53.680 --> 44:56.021
No, no, no, no, you
don't get to do this.

44:57.120 --> 44:59.302
It took me years to forget.

44:59.360 --> 45:02.862
You are dead to me. You are dead!

45:02.920 --> 45:04.670
I'm not asking for forgiveness.

45:04.760 --> 45:06.988
God can forgive me, that's his job.

45:07.040 --> 45:11.031
- You have no control over me.
- We should never be together.

45:11.080 --> 45:12.944
I hate you.

45:13.000 --> 45:16.388
You crushed me heart and
you stained me soul.

45:16.480 --> 45:18.389
Fuck you.

45:18.480 --> 45:21.231
No, darlin'.

45:23.160 --> 45:25.547
Fuck you.

45:34.200 --> 45:35.870
Are we ready to do this?

45:41.240 --> 45:42.580
Let's roll!

45:43.680 --> 45:46.590
Just, uh, try to act natural.

45:46.680 --> 45:49.067
Yeah. I, I don't know
what that means.

45:49.120 --> 45:51.666
What do we have here?

45:53.200 --> 45:57.385
Two perps, one box, red.

45:57.480 --> 45:59.344
I betcha there's something in that.

46:02.000 --> 46:03.909
Here we go. They're on the move.

46:03.960 --> 46:06.745
Thank you. I needed to know that.

46:06.800 --> 46:10.621
Please continue to point out the
obvious to me as it comes up.

46:10.680 --> 46:13.545
- You're starting the car.
- OK. That's enough.

46:13.600 --> 46:17.500
- You're putting the car into gear.
- I so very much want to stab you

46:17.560 --> 46:19.185
in the face and throat.

46:19.240 --> 46:21.468
With your magic pen, no doubt.

46:28.720 --> 46:32.905
Saturday, ten AM. Guy walks
into the border station.

46:32.960 --> 46:34.519
And, man, will you
please wear a suit?

46:34.520 --> 46:36.987
No offense, but you
look like a slutty elf.

46:37.040 --> 46:40.986
What... is "elf"?

46:42.320 --> 46:44.309
<i>The station gets a
call the day before</i>

46:44.400 --> 46:46.343
<i>from a woman they think is Olga.</i>

46:46.400 --> 46:48.628
I cannot make it, but
my colleague, Philippe,

46:48.680 --> 46:50.782
- he should be there.
<i>- Hello.</i>

46:50.840 --> 46:54.501
Oh. I think I chipped a tooth.

47:05.440 --> 47:08.430
<i>Olga gets a call the
day before from a man</i>

47:08.480 --> 47:10.070
<i>she thinks is from the border.</i>

47:10.120 --> 47:13.349
So, while we'll not be
requiring your services,

47:13.400 --> 47:15.980
we will, of course, still pay.

47:31.680 --> 47:34.021
- Yeah, where're we at?
- I got Guy on the other line.

47:34.120 --> 47:36.302
OK, I'm in. How will
I know where it is?

47:36.360 --> 47:40.431
It's pink and three feet tall.
You're a Frenchman, you'll find it.

47:48.120 --> 47:51.224
<i>Like Ponch said, with no
security cameras in the room,</i>

47:51.280 --> 47:54.111
<i>Guy can make the switch.</i>

47:54.160 --> 47:56.262
All right. We got an hour to go.

47:56.320 --> 47:59.981
- Did you get the nylons?
- I did indeed.

48:00.040 --> 48:02.620
- One?
- Well, it says one pair.

48:02.680 --> 48:05.260
- One pair? Like a pair of pants.
- Yeah.

48:05.360 --> 48:07.588
Well, I'm sorry, Mr. Condescending,

48:07.640 --> 48:09.230
I don't buy a whole lot
of fuckin' pantyhose.

48:09.320 --> 48:10.990
- Fishnets?
- Yes.

48:11.040 --> 48:13.540
Put these over our heads we'll
look like a couple of waffles.

48:40.600 --> 48:42.782
This is just great.

48:42.840 --> 48:44.146
OK, let's go.

48:56.600 --> 48:59.180
- Yeah?
- Finished.

48:59.240 --> 49:01.707
All right, Crunch, you're up.

49:14.440 --> 49:18.704
No. Something's not right.

49:21.680 --> 49:24.750
- OK, here we go.
- What are you doing?

49:24.800 --> 49:28.950
This is usually how it works. Perps
go on the move, cops get moving.

49:29.000 --> 49:32.024
A little pro tip for you:
"perps", short for perpetrators.

49:32.080 --> 49:36.504
Just trust me for a second.
Don't switch the engine on.

49:42.480 --> 49:45.390
Seriously, what are we doing?
Why do I listen to you?

49:46.640 --> 49:48.549
You're being distracted.

49:48.600 --> 49:51.943
Like at the Quebec airport.

49:56.680 --> 49:59.021
The border. They're at the border.

50:09.720 --> 50:11.470
They stopped following us.

50:22.440 --> 50:25.669
Pick up. Come on, pick up.

50:29.600 --> 50:31.543
Two minutes away. Come on!

50:32.640 --> 50:33.741
Whoo!

50:51.600 --> 50:52.986
I'm clear.

51:03.720 --> 51:07.347
I'm trying to, I'm trying to.
This is what I...

51:07.400 --> 51:11.061
Hey! Hey! Here we go. Here we go.

51:14.360 --> 51:15.746
Whoo!

51:17.480 --> 51:19.662
Atta boy, Crunch!

51:22.240 --> 51:24.911
All right, just like the old days.

51:24.960 --> 51:27.506
Yeah, the old days where
you threw me to the cops?

51:27.600 --> 51:29.907
Or the old days where a
one-eyed pirate steals my bike?

51:29.960 --> 51:33.587
Uh, uh, uh. Now, now, gentlemen.

51:33.640 --> 51:35.663
Let us drink to James.

51:35.720 --> 51:38.710
- To James!
- To James!

51:40.680 --> 51:43.386
And to Nicky Boy. One for the ages.

51:48.880 --> 51:52.029
- Now you take a bow, Guy.
- Moi?

51:52.080 --> 51:55.707
Four days to fake a
500-year-old masterpiece.

51:55.800 --> 51:57.584
Oh, to have your talent, lad.

51:57.640 --> 52:00.710
It was an inspired effort. I admit.

52:00.800 --> 52:02.948
But I am no Yves Chaudron.

52:03.000 --> 52:06.388
Who's that, Yeeves Show-row?

52:06.440 --> 52:07.780
Stay, Crunch. You'll like this.

52:07.800 --> 52:09.231
Nah, I've heard this
tale a time or two.

52:09.280 --> 52:11.269
- I gotta take a piss.
- Come on, Crunch.

52:11.320 --> 52:13.502
Wait. Who's Yves Shmo-boh?

52:13.560 --> 52:15.981
I shall tell you of Yves Chaudron.

52:16.040 --> 52:19.144
For this is a story of inspiration.

52:19.240 --> 52:21.707
He was everything I aspire to be.

52:21.760 --> 52:24.784
A master, a legend.

52:24.840 --> 52:29.025
A man so gifted his work
would make angels cry.

52:29.120 --> 52:34.750
He was the one true talent behind
the greatest art theft in history.

52:34.800 --> 52:38.268
The theft of the Mona Lisa.

52:40.040 --> 52:42.825
<i>The story begins in Paris, 1911.</i>

52:42.880 --> 52:45.142
<i>Not with Chaudron,
but with an Italian,</i>

52:45.200 --> 52:47.382
<i>a poor carpenter named Perugia</i>

52:47.440 --> 52:51.465
<i>who, a few months before the theft,
works a contract at the Louvre.</i>

52:51.560 --> 52:55.221
<i>As with any menial job,
he learns many menial things.</i>

52:55.280 --> 52:57.144
<i>Such as where the
entrances and exits are,</i>

52:57.200 --> 52:59.951
<i>the guards' names,
rotations and the like.</i>

53:00.000 --> 53:03.946
<i>Little did he know that this
otherwise useless information</i>

53:04.000 --> 53:06.387
<i>would prove to be quite important.</i>

53:06.440 --> 53:09.623
<i>For it is when Perugia's
contract ends</i>

53:09.680 --> 53:12.624
<i>that his destiny begins.</i>

53:12.680 --> 53:16.341
<i>Fate taps Perugia on the shoulder.</i>

53:16.400 --> 53:20.664
<i>Eduardo de Valfierno,
a criminal mastermind.</i>

53:20.720 --> 53:25.064
<i>Valfierno asks Perugia
to steal the Mona Lisa</i>

53:25.120 --> 53:29.464
<i>for $30, 000. It's like
a million back then,</i>

53:29.560 --> 53:33.585
<i>an offer a poor carpenter
could never refuse.</i>

53:33.640 --> 53:36.425
<i>The adventure of the theft
is a story in and of itself.</i>

53:36.520 --> 53:39.863
<i>In short, through luck,
cunning, lazy security</i>

53:39.920 --> 53:43.581
<i>and the horrible disadvantage of
being Italian, he actually succeeds.</i>

53:43.640 --> 53:49.031
<i>The carpenter steals the Mona Lisa
and the theft makes world news.</i>

53:53.000 --> 53:55.262
<i>As promised,
he produces the Mona Lisa.</i>

53:55.320 --> 53:59.061
<i>Valfierno produces the money.
But he makes a strange request.</i>

53:59.120 --> 54:01.507
<i>He asks him to hold on to
her just a little longer</i>

54:01.560 --> 54:04.311
<i>so he can arrange for
her transit overseas.</i>

54:04.360 --> 54:07.304
<i>Perugia agrees and waits,</i>

54:07.360 --> 54:10.031
<i>and waits and waits.</i>

54:10.080 --> 54:12.501
His story ends here.

54:12.600 --> 54:15.704
And it is now that I tell
you of Yves Chaudron.

54:15.760 --> 54:17.942
<i>Six months before the theft,</i>

54:18.000 --> 54:21.946
<i>Valfierno commissions Yves Chaudron,
the world's greatest forger,</i>

54:22.000 --> 54:25.263
<i>to reproduce the Mona Lisa
six times and perfect,</i>

54:25.360 --> 54:28.350
<i>an Herculean task only
Chaudron could accomplish.</i>

54:28.400 --> 54:30.389
<i>Valfierno then sails to America</i>

54:30.440 --> 54:32.861
<i>and finds six of the
greediest art collectors</i>

54:32.920 --> 54:35.182
<i>and poses this question to them:</i>

54:35.240 --> 54:38.105
<i>"Should the Mona Lisa
suddenly become available,</i>

54:38.160 --> 54:40.831
<i>would you pay three hundred
thousand dollars for it?"</i>

54:40.920 --> 54:45.264
<i>He asks all six,
and all six say, "Yes."</i>

54:45.320 --> 54:49.345
<i>And that is when Valfierno pays
Perugia to steal the Mona Lisa.</i>

54:49.400 --> 54:51.867
<i>He then ships Chaudron's
perfect fakes</i>

54:51.920 --> 54:55.388
<i>and collects $1.8 million.</i>

54:55.440 --> 54:58.305
<i>A fortune beyond comprehension.</i>

55:01.080 --> 55:05.390
<i>You see, all he needed
was the news of the theft,</i>

55:05.440 --> 55:08.828
<i>not the Mona Lisa.</i>

55:08.880 --> 55:14.828
<i>To him, she herself, is worthless.</i>

55:16.760 --> 55:20.910
And that is the story of the
theft of the Mona Lisa.

55:23.440 --> 55:26.430
I first heard that story
when I was a small boy.

55:26.480 --> 55:31.586
I knew even then I wanted to have the
skills to pull something that great off.

55:31.680 --> 55:34.989
- And that's why I do what I do.
- I do it for the ladies.

55:39.080 --> 55:41.660
Well, here's to tomorrow,

55:41.720 --> 55:44.744
and the Reverend gets his goods
and we get our just rewards.

55:44.800 --> 55:47.983
- Tomorrow!
- Tomorrow!

56:02.280 --> 56:05.065
Ohhh, fuck.

56:05.120 --> 56:08.110
Oh, Jesus, Mary and Joseph.

56:08.160 --> 56:12.629
I, I taste an ashtray
and battery acid

56:12.720 --> 56:15.471
and, like, stripper perfume.

56:15.520 --> 56:19.784
So, we headed for Detroit? Finish
things up with the Reverend, or what?

56:19.840 --> 56:22.341
Yeah, that's right.
We all just pile into the car

56:22.440 --> 56:25.828
like the Brady Bunch and just
breeze on into the States, right?

56:25.880 --> 56:27.584
They already flagged me
for coming over here.

56:27.640 --> 56:29.390
- Yeah, me too.
- Me too.

56:29.440 --> 56:33.147
They don't like me a lot either, so...
what exactly is your plan?

56:33.240 --> 56:37.425
Well, we need someone with a
clean sheet. Francie, you're up.

56:37.480 --> 56:38.661
Me?!

56:45.880 --> 56:48.586
Really? Why am I wearing this shit?

56:48.640 --> 56:50.230
Because Interpol knows
what you look like.

56:50.280 --> 56:53.543
OK, but don't the Amish
ride horse and carriages?

56:54.800 --> 56:57.346
- Well, you're progressive.
- I can't fucking do this!

56:57.400 --> 57:00.549
Well, you better get your best
Brando on, hoss, 'cause we need you.

57:00.640 --> 57:03.425
Yeah, look, Francie,
it's not <i>The King's Speech.</i>

57:03.520 --> 57:06.385
Come here. You got two lines:

57:06.480 --> 57:09.311
"Going to Detroit."
And "Nothing to declare."

57:09.400 --> 57:11.628
You're gonna be great.

57:11.680 --> 57:14.784
- I'll meet him there.
- Oh. Will you?

57:14.840 --> 57:18.262
Yeah. Hey, look, somebody's
got to be in Detroit

57:18.320 --> 57:21.947
- to close the deal with the Reverend.
- Nicky, I'm goin' with ya.

57:22.040 --> 57:24.063
- We're both hiding in the trunk.
- The trunk?

57:24.120 --> 57:26.507
I'm not hidin' in a trunk.

57:26.560 --> 57:29.425
Well, then no one's
going to Detroit.

